SIMPLE: denominator
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Denominator
<hw>De*nom"i*na`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>d⟦eacute⟧nominateur</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that
which, gives a name; origin or source of a name.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This opinion that Aram . . . was the father and
<qex>denomination</qex> of the Syrians in general.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arith.)</fld> <def>That number placed below the
line in common fractions which shows into how many parts the integer or
unit is divided.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Thus, in ⟦frac35⟧, 5 is the <xex>denominator</xex>,
showing that the integer is divided into five parts; and the numerator,
3, shows how many parts are taken.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Alg.)</fld> <def>That part of any expression under
a fractional form which is situated below the horizontal line signifying
division.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense, the <xex>denominator</xex> is not
necessarily a number, but may be any expression, either positive or
negative, real or imaginary.</note> <rj><au>Davies & Peck (Math.
Dict.)</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>common denominator</b></col> <cd>a number which can
divide either of two or more other numbers without leaving a remainder
in any of the divisions; <as>as, 2 and 4 are <ex>common
denominators</ex> of 12 and 28.</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>greatest common
denominator</b></col> <cd>the largest <cref>common denominator</cref> of
two or more numbers; <as>as, 9 is the <ex>greatest common
denominator</ex> of 18 and 27.</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Denotable</ent>⟦br⟧
